The Interview That Turned Into a Gym Session ‚Äî and Then a Robbery Chronicles of a Dev Who Just Wanted a 120K Job in WestlandsIn 2019, I applied for a developer interview through LinkedIn. The job ad said:‚ÄúTech startup hiring now! Salary 120K+. Interview in Westlands. Come prepared.‚Äù So far, so good. But then I saw this: ‚ÄúDress official... but carry gym wear and sport shoes.‚ÄùWeird, but okay. Maybe they value wellness culture or have a quirky onboarding process. It‚Äôs 2019, right? By 8:30 AM, We Were All SeatedWe came dressed in suits, laptops ready, resumes sharpened. Then someone walked in and said:‚ÄúAt our company, we respect work-life balance. All new hires must experience our paid gym sessions.‚Äù So we were told to change into gym clothes and head to Room C49 on the 6th floor. We left our laptops, phones, shoes, and official clothes in the changing room, thinking we‚Äôd be back in 45 mins. But the ‚Äú45-Minute Wellness Session‚Äù‚Ä¶ Turned Into a 2-Hour TrapAerobics. Motivation speeches. Some random zumba. It felt more like orientation for a pyramid scheme than a job interview. When we came back downstairs‚Ä¶The changing room was locked.We asked security. They said:‚ÄúC49? That room has had no tenant for 6 months.‚ÄùLaptops ‚Äî gone. Phones ‚Äî gone. Our hopes ‚Äî vanished like an NFT market cap.We ran to Parklands Police Station, only to be told:‚ÄúOh yeah, we know the place. You‚Äôre not the first group.‚Äù Final Scene Me. In boxers. No fare. No phone. No laptop. Trekking to town like a confused athlete who missed the Olympics. If an interview asks for gym clothes, it's not a job ‚Äî it's a workout scam and always ‚Äî always ‚Äî carry backup fare. The Interview That Turned Into a Gym Session ‚Äî and Then a Robbery Chronicles of a Dev Who Just Wanted a 120K Job in WestlandsIn 2019, I applied for a developer interview through LinkedIn. The job ad said:‚ÄúTech startup hiring now! Salary 120K+. Interview in Westlands. Come prepared.‚Äù So far, so good. But then I saw this: ‚ÄúDress official... but carry gym wear and sport shoes.‚ÄùWeird, but okay. Maybe they value wellness culture or have a quirky onboarding process. It‚Äôs 2019, right? By 8:30 AM, We Were All SeatedWe came dressed in suits, laptops ready, resumes sharpened. Then someone walked in and said:‚ÄúAt our company, we respect work-life balance. All new hires must experience our paid gym sessions.‚Äù So we were told to change into gym clothes and head to Room C49 on the 6th floor. We left our laptops, phones, shoes, and official clothes in the changing room, thinking we‚Äôd be back in 45 mins. But the ‚Äú45-Minute Wellness Session‚Äù‚Ä¶ Turned Into a 2-Hour TrapAerobics. Motivation speeches. Some random zumba. It felt more like orientation for a pyramid scheme than a job interview. When we came back downstairs‚Ä¶The changing room was locked.We asked security. They said:‚ÄúC49? That room has had no tenant for 6 months.‚ÄùLaptops ‚Äî gone. Phones ‚Äî gone. Our hopes ‚Äî vanished like an NFT market cap.We ran to Parklands Police Station, only to be told:‚ÄúOh yeah, we know the place. You‚Äôre not the first group.‚Äù Final Scene Me. In boxers. No fare. No phone. No laptop. Trekking to town like a confused athlete who missed the Olympics. If an interview asks for gym clothes, it's not a job ‚Äî it's a workout scam and always ‚Äî always ‚Äî carry backup fare. Nairobi is unpredictable.hashtag#JobSearchChronicles hashtag#NairobiHustle hashtag#DeveloperLife hashtag#LinkedInRealTalk hashtag#ScamAlert hashtag#WorkLifeBalanceGoneWrong hashtag#StayWoke hashtag#trending hashtag#Jobs hashtag#africa

üöÄ Introducing EventX ‚Äì A Universal Event Manager for .NET Apps üß†‚öôÔ∏èIn modern apps, components often need to react to things happening elsewhere ‚Äî a product added to cart, a user logging in, a notification being dismissed. But wiring this up cleanly across unrelated components can be messy, especially in larger Blazor or MAUI apps.That‚Äôs where EventX comes in ‚Äî a lightweight, thread-safe C# library that brings event-driven architecture to your .NET apps, with zero boilerplate.üîß What it does:üîÅ Publish/subscribe to events across the app (sync & async)üîí Strongly-typed and memory-leak safeüö´ Auto-remove listeners with .Once()‚úÖ Works in Blazor (Server/WASM), MAUI, WPF, etc.üì¶ Real-World Use Cases:üõí Mini Cart updates in E-commerce appsüîî Toast Notifications triggered globallyüì£ Multi-tab communication (via BroadcastChannel)üß† Loose coupling between services and UIüïµÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Debugging memory leaks with scoped unsubscriptionHere's the beauty: with EventX, your components don‚Äôt need to know who is listening ‚Äî they just fire an event, and magic happens üí•Visit the link to know more:https://lnkd.in/dvjefT8Ghashtag#dotnet hashtag#csharp hashtag#blazor hashtag#blazorwasm hashtag#dotnetcore hashtag#eventdrivenarchitecture hashtag#developerexperience hashtag#webdevelopment hashtag#frontenddevelopment hashtag#backenddevelopment hashtag#aspnetcore hashtag#softwarearchitecture hashtag#opensource hashtag#dependencyinjection hashtag#eventdriven hashtag#devtools hashtag#programming hashtag#softwareengineering hashtag#reactivity hashtag#multitab hashtag#browserapi hashtag#broadcastchannel hashtag#scalability hashtag#modulararchitecture hashtag#cleanarchitecture

üîπ ASP.NET Core Middleware Pipeline ‚Äì Part 4: Static Files MiddlewareOnce HTTPS is enforced, the next step in the pipeline is enabling your app to serve static content like images, CSS, JavaScript, and other assets.üóÇÔ∏è What does Static Files Middleware do? It allows your ASP.NET Core app to serve files directly from the wwwroot folder (or any configured directory) without needing any controller logic.üì¶ UseStaticFiles() This middleware scans for static files and returns them if found, bypassing the rest of the pipeline.app.UseStaticFiles();üìù For example, if you have:wwwroot/css/site.cssA browser can request it at:https://lnkd.in/dnn8CzJb‚ö†Ô∏è Security Tip: By default, only the wwwroot folder is accessible. Avoid serving sensitive files by accidentally exposing other directories.üß† Best Practice: Place UseStaticFiles() early in the pipeline so static content is returned before more complex processing (like routing or authentication).üöÄ Coming up next: Routing Middleware ‚Äî the backbone of request processing.hashtag#ASPNETCore hashtag#Middleware hashtag#DotNet hashtag#StaticFiles hashtag#WebDev hashtag#CSharp hashtag#BackendDevelopment

üöÄ Introducing EventX ‚Äì A Universal Event Manager for .NET Apps üß†‚öôÔ∏èIn modern apps, components often need to react to things happening elsewhere ‚Äî a product added to cart, a user logging in, a notification being dismissed. But wiring this up cleanly across unrelated components can be messy, especially in larger Blazor or MAUI apps.That‚Äôs where EventX comes in ‚Äî a lightweight, thread-safe C# library that brings event-driven architecture to your .NET apps, with zero boilerplate.üîß What it does:üîÅ Publish/subscribe to events across the app (sync & async)üîí Strongly-typed and memory-leak safeüö´ Auto-remove listeners with .Once()‚úÖ Works in Blazor (Server/WASM), MAUI, WPF, etc.üì¶ Real-World Use Cases:üõí Mini Cart updates in E-commerce appsüîî Toast Notifications triggered globallyüì£ Multi-tab communication (via BroadcastChannel)üß† Loose coupling between services and UIüïµÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Debugging memory leaks with scoped unsubscriptionHere's the beauty: with EventX, your components don‚Äôt need to know who is listening ‚Äî they just fire an event, and magic happens üí•Visit the link to know more:https://lnkd.in/dvjefT8Ghashtag#dotnet hashtag#csharp hashtag#blazor hashtag#blazorwasm hashtag#dotnetcore hashtag#eventdrivenarchitecture hashtag#developerexperience hashtag#webdevelopment hashtag#frontenddevelopment hashtag#backenddevelopment hashtag#aspnetcore hashtag#softwarearchitecture hashtag#opensource hashtag#dependencyinjection hashtag#eventdriven hashtag#devtools hashtag#programming hashtag#softwareengineering hashtag#reactivity hashtag#multitab hashtag#browserapi hashtag#broadcastchannel hashtag#scalability hashtag#modulararchitecture hashtag#cleanarchitecture

üîπ ASP.NET Core Middleware Pipeline ‚Äì Part 4: Static Files MiddlewareOnce HTTPS is enforced, the next step in the pipeline is enabling your app to serve static content like images, CSS, JavaScript, and other assets.üóÇÔ∏è What does Static Files Middleware do? It allows your ASP.NET Core app to serve files directly from the wwwroot folder (or any configured directory) without needing any controller logic.üì¶ UseStaticFiles() This middleware scans for static files and returns them if found, bypassing the rest of the pipeline.app.UseStaticFiles();üìù For example, if you have:wwwroot/css/site.cssA browser can request it at:https://lnkd.in/dnn8CzJb‚ö†Ô∏è Security Tip: By default, only the wwwroot folder is accessible. Avoid serving sensitive files by accidentally exposing other directories.üß† Best Practice: Place UseStaticFiles() early in the pipeline so static content is returned before more complex processing (like routing or authentication).üöÄ Coming up next: Routing Middleware ‚Äî the backbone of request processing.hashtag#ASPNETCore hashtag#Middleware hashtag#DotNet hashtag#StaticFiles hashtag#WebDev hashtag#CSharp hashtag#BackendDevelopment

üöÄ Introducing EventX ‚Äì A Universal Event Manager for .NET Apps üß†‚öôÔ∏èIn modern apps, components often need to react to things happening elsewhere ‚Äî a product added to cart, a user logging in, a notification being dismissed. But wiring this up cleanly across unrelated components can be messy, especially in larger Blazor or MAUI apps.That‚Äôs where EventX comes in ‚Äî a lightweight, thread-safe C# library that brings event-driven architecture to your .NET apps, with zero boilerplate.üîß What it does:üîÅ Publish/subscribe to events across the app (sync & async)üîí Strongly-typed and memory-leak safeüö´ Auto-remove listeners with .Once()‚úÖ Works in Blazor (Server/WASM), MAUI, WPF, etc.üì¶ Real-World Use Cases:üõí Mini Cart updates in E-commerce appsüîî Toast Notifications triggered globallyüì£ Multi-tab communication (via BroadcastChannel)üß† Loose coupling between services and UIüïµÔ∏è‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Debugging memory leaks with scoped unsubscriptionHere's the beauty: with EventX, your components don‚Äôt need to know who is listening ‚Äî they just fire an event, and magic happens üí•Visit the link to know more:https://lnkd.in/dvjefT8Ghashtag#dotnet hashtag#csharp hashtag#blazor hashtag#blazorwasm hashtag#dotnetcore hashtag#eventdrivenarchitecture hashtag#developerexperience hashtag#webdevelopment hashtag#frontenddevelopment hashtag#backenddevelopment hashtag#aspnetcore hashtag#softwarearchitecture hashtag#opensource hashtag#dependencyinjection hashtag#eventdriven hashtag#devtools hashtag#programming hashtag#softwareengineering hashtag#reactivity hashtag#multitab hashtag#browserapi hashtag#broadcastchannel hashtag#scalability hashtag#modulararchitecture hashtag#cleanarchitecture

üîπ ASP.NET Core Middleware Pipeline ‚Äì Part 4: Static Files MiddlewareOnce HTTPS is enforced, the next step in the pipeline is enabling your app to serve static content like images, CSS, JavaScript, and other assets.üóÇÔ∏è What does Static Files Middleware do? It allows your ASP.NET Core app to serve files directly from the wwwroot folder (or any configured directory) without needing any controller logic.üì¶ UseStaticFiles() This middleware scans for static files and returns them if found, bypassing the rest of the pipeline.app.UseStaticFiles();üìù For example, if you have:wwwroot/css/site.cssA browser can request it at:https://lnkd.in/dnn8CzJb‚ö†Ô∏è Security Tip: By default, only the wwwroot folder is accessible. Avoid serving sensitive files by accidentally exposing other directories.üß† Best Practice: Place UseStaticFiles() early in the pipeline so static content is returned before more complex processing (like routing or authentication).üöÄ Coming up next: Routing Middleware ‚Äî the backbone of request processing.hashtag#ASPNETCore hashtag#Middleware hashtag#DotNet hashtag#StaticFiles hashtag#WebDev hashtag#CSharp hashtag#BackendDevelopment

It allows your ASP.NET Core app to serve files directly from the wwwroot folder (or any configured directory) without needing any controller logic.üì¶ UseStaticFiles() This middleware scans for static files and returns them if found, bypassing the rest of the pipeline.app.UseStaticFiles();üìù For example, if you have:wwwroot/css/site.cssA browser can request it at:https://lnkd.in/dnn8CzJb‚ö†Ô∏è Security Tip: By default, only the wwwroot folder is accessible.
